---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Fundamentals 10 — Boyd Dubois"
  description="Unfolding case study: Postoperative Pain Management and Care (FUN-10)"
>

  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/fundamentals/`}>Fundamentals</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Fundamentals 10 — Boyd Dubois</span>
  </div>

  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">Postoperative / Musculoskeletal</span>
    <h1>Fundamentals 10 — Boyd Dubois</h1>
    <p class="case-subtitle">Postoperative Pain Management After Total Hip Arthroplasty</p>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>👤 Boyd Dubois, Older Adult Male</span>
      <span>⏱ Scenario: 20 – 25 minutes</span>
      <span>💬 Debrief: 20 – 25 minutes</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <strong>📖 How to Use This Unfolding Case Study</strong>
    <p>Work through each phase in order. Information is revealed progressively — exactly as it would be in a real clinical encounter. Before reading each answer, pause and reason through the question yourself. Use the <strong>▶ Reveal Answer</strong> toggles to check your thinking.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- PHASE 1 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase1">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 1</span>
      <h2>You Arrive at the Bedside</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You are the morning nurse on a surgical unit. Boyd Dubois underwent a total right hip arthroplasty yesterday. He is postoperative day 1. He is grimacing in bed and has not used his incentive spirometer this morning.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📋 Handoff Report</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Patient</th><td>Boyd Dubois</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Age</th><td>Older adult male</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Primary Dx</th><td>Total right hip arthroplasty — postoperative day 1</td></tr>
            <tr><th>History</th><td>Osteoarthritis; hypothyroidism; GERD/peptic ulcer history</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Code Status</th><td>Full code</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Allergies</th><td>Review MAR</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Last pain med</th><td>Morphine IV 2 mg × 4 hours ago</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💊 Postoperative Medications</h3>
        <ul class="med-list">
          <li><strong>Morphine</strong> — IV/SQ for moderate-severe pain</li>
          <li><strong>Hydrocodone/Acetaminophen</strong> — PO for moderate pain</li>
          <li><strong>Acetaminophen</strong> — PO for mild-moderate pain</li>
          <li><strong>Enoxaparin (Lovenox)</strong> — SQ DVT prophylaxis</li>
          <li><strong>Levothyroxine</strong> — PO (hypothyroidism — must continue)</li>
          <li><strong>Pantoprazole</strong> — PO (GERD/GI protection with opioids)</li>
          <li>Lactated Ringer's IV — fluid maintenance</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🚪 Entering the Room — What You Observe</h3>
      <p>Boyd is lying in bed at about 30° elevation. He is grimacing. He rates his pain as 8/10. The incentive spirometer is on his bedside table, untouched. He says, "It hurts too much to breathe deeply. I just can't do it." His O₂ sat is 93%.</p>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: What is the connection between pain control and respiratory complications? What is your first priority?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Pain → Splinting → Atelectasis → Pneumonia:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Uncontrolled pain causes patients to take shallow breaths to avoid pain (splinting)</li>
          <li>Shallow breathing → alveoli collapse → atelectasis (most common postop respiratory complication)</li>
          <li>Atelectasis → retained secretions → pneumonia</li>
          <li><strong>Effective pain management IS respiratory care</strong> — they cannot be separated</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Priority: Address pain first</strong> so Boyd can tolerate deep breathing exercises.</p>
        <ol>
          <li>Perform full pain assessment (OPQRST)</li>
          <li>Administer ordered analgesic (pain 8/10 warrants intervention)</li>
          <li>Reassess SpO₂ and pain in 30–60 minutes</li>
          <li>Once pain is controlled, coach incentive spirometry</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You perform a complete pain assessment before administering medication…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 2 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase2">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 2</span>
      <h2>Complete Pain Assessment</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Using the OPQRST framework, you assess Boyd's pain before making any medication decisions.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📊 OPQRST Pain Assessment — Boyd</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>O — Onset/Timing</th><td>Constant since surgery; worse this morning with shift change and movement</td></tr>
            <tr><th>P — Precipitating/Palliating</th><td>Worse with movement and deep breathing; slightly better when completely still</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Q — Quality</th><td>"Deep aching and throbbing at my hip"</td></tr>
            <tr><th>R — Region/Radiation</th><td>Right hip and groin; does not radiate</td></tr>
            <tr><th>S — Severity</th><td>8/10 current; 6/10 goal</td></tr>
            <tr><th>T — Treatment/Impact</th><td>Last morphine 4 hours ago; pain preventing deep breathing and mobilization</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>📊 Current Vital Signs</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <tbody>
            <tr><th>Temperature</th><td>37.8°C (100°F) — low-grade (possible early atelectasis)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Blood Pressure</th><td>136/84 mmHg</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Heart Rate</th><td>96 bpm (tachycardia — pain response)</td></tr>
            <tr><th>Respiratory Rate</th><td>20 breaths/min; shallow</td></tr>
            <tr><th>SpO₂</th><td><span class="text-danger">93%</span></td></tr>
            <tr><th>Lung sounds</th><td>Crackles at right base; diminished left base</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Boyd's temp is 100°F. What is the most likely cause 24 hours post-op, and what does it mean?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Low-grade fever at 24–48 hours post-op = most likely atelectasis.</strong></p>
        <p><strong>"Wind, Water, Wound, Walking, Wonder drugs" — the 5 W's of postoperative fever:</strong></p>
        <table class="data-table" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
          <thead><tr><th>Timeframe</th><th>Likely Cause</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>24–48 hours</td><td><strong>Wind</strong> — atelectasis (pulmonary collapse)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>48–72 hours</td><td><strong>Water</strong> — UTI (urinary tract infection)</td></tr>
            <tr><td>72 hours+</td><td><strong>Wound</strong> — surgical site infection</td></tr>
            <tr><td>5–7 days</td><td><strong>Walking</strong> — DVT/PE</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Any time</td><td><strong>Wonder drugs</strong> — drug fever from medications</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
        <p><strong>Action:</strong> Boyd's crackles + low-grade fever + SpO₂ 93% + not using IS = classic early atelectasis. Pain management is the intervention — get Boyd breathing deeply.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You administer analgesic and prepare for breathing exercises…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 3 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase3">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 3</span>
      <h2>Multimodal Pain Management and Incentive Spirometry</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You administer acetaminophen PO and morphine IV per order. 30 minutes later, Boyd's pain is 5/10. SpO₂ is still 93%. You now coach incentive spirometry.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💊 Multimodal Pain Management</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>Approach</th><th>Examples</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>Opioids</strong></td><td>Morphine, hydrocodone — moderate-severe pain</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Non-opioid analgesics</strong></td><td>Acetaminophen — reduces opioid requirements (opioid sparing)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>NSAIDs</strong></td><td>Ibuprofen, ketorolac — anti-inflammatory; caution with GI history</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Non-pharmacologic</strong></td><td>Ice pack to hip, repositioning, relaxation, distraction, splinting for cough</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Regional anesthesia</strong></td><td>Nerve block, epidural — targeted; reduces systemic opioid need</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🌬️ Incentive Spirometry Teaching</h3>
        <ol>
          <li>Pre-medicate: administer analgesic 30–60 min before IS coaching</li>
          <li>Position: Semi-Fowler's or High-Fowler's</li>
          <li>Teach splinting: have Boyd hold pillow firmly against right hip</li>
          <li>"Breathe in slowly and as deeply as you can through the mouthpiece"</li>
          <li>"Hold the breath for 3 seconds — then breathe out slowly"</li>
          <li>"Repeat 10 times every 1–2 hours while you are awake"</li>
          <li>Encourage and record achievement volume</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Why is pantoprazole ordered for Boyd? What is the morphine risk to monitor for?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Pantoprazole (proton pump inhibitor) for Boyd:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Boyd has a history of GERD and peptic ulcer disease</li>
          <li>Opioids slow GI motility (constipation risk) and may worsen GI symptoms</li>
          <li>PPI reduces gastric acid production, protecting the stomach lining from ulceration — especially important when opioids and possible NSAIDs are in use</li>
        </ul>
        <p><strong>Primary morphine risk to monitor:</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Respiratory depression</strong> — monitor respiratory rate and SpO₂ after administration; hold if RR &lt; 12</li>
          <li>Sedation scale — assess level of consciousness</li>
          <li>Constipation — start bowel regimen concurrently</li>
          <li>Nausea — have anti-emetic available</li>
          <li>Hypotension — monitor BP especially in older adults</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ With respiratory care underway, you teach hip precautions…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 4 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase4">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 4</span>
      <h2>Hip Replacement Precautions</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">Boyd will need to follow specific hip precautions for 6–12 weeks to prevent dislocation of the new joint prosthesis. He asks, "What do I need to watch out for?"</p>
    <div class="callout callout-warning">
      <strong>⚠️ Hip Dislocation Signs — EMERGENCY</strong>
      <p>Sudden severe pain · External rotation of operative leg · Leg appears shorter than the other · Report immediately to provider</p>
    </div>
    <div class="scene-box">
      <h3>🦴 Total Hip Arthroplasty Precautions (Must Teach)</h3>
      <table class="data-table">
        <thead><tr><th>Precaution</th><th>Rule</th><th>Why</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>No hip flexion &gt; 90°</strong></td><td>Do not bend the hip past a right angle</td><td>Prevents anterior dislocation of prosthesis</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>No adduction</strong></td><td>Do not cross legs or bring operative leg past midline</td><td>Prevents posterior dislocation</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>No internal rotation</strong></td><td>Do not turn toes inward</td><td>Prevents prosthesis from dislocating</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Raised toilet seat</strong></td><td>Use elevated toilet seat at home</td><td>Prevents excessive hip flexion during toileting</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Abduction pillow in bed</strong></td><td>Keep legs apart when supine</td><td>Prevents adduction and dislocation while sleeping</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Rising from chair</strong></td><td>Scoot to edge first; then stand keeping hip extended</td><td>Prevents hip flexion beyond 90° during stand</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Boyd asks if he can cross his legs like he usually does. How do you respond?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p>"Mr. Dubois, I understand that's a habit — but after your hip replacement, crossing your legs is one of the most important things to avoid. It can cause your new hip to pop out of the socket — what we call a dislocation. That would be a very painful emergency requiring more surgery."</p>
        <p>Then teach:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>"We will leave an abduction pillow between your legs in bed to help you remember."</li>
          <li>"At home, you'll need a raised toilet seat and a grabber or shoehorn to avoid bending too far."</li>
          <li>"Physical therapy will go over all of these with you too — and they'll make sure you can do them safely."</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Use teach-back: "Can you tell me the three main things to avoid with your new hip?" (No bending past 90°, no crossing legs, no turning toes in)</p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You administer enoxaparin and complete the remaining medication tasks…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 5 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase5">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 5</span>
      <h2>Enoxaparin Administration and Neurovascular Assessment</h2>
    </div>
    <p class="phase-intro">You prepare to administer the ordered enoxaparin (Lovenox) SQ and perform your neurovascular assessment of the operative extremity.</p>
    <div class="info-grid">
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>💉 Enoxaparin (Lovenox) SQ — Key Points</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Inject into <strong>abdomen</strong> (alternating sides; avoid 2 inches of umbilicus)</li>
          <li>Do <strong>NOT expel the air bubble</strong> in the prefilled syringe — it follows the drug and reduces bruising</li>
          <li>Do <strong>NOT aspirate</strong> before injecting SQ</li>
          <li>Do <strong>NOT rub the site</strong> after injection — causes bruising and alters absorption</li>
          <li>Monitor for bleeding: bruising, petechiae, hematoma, blood in stool/urine</li>
          <li>Monitor platelet count (HIT — heparin-induced thrombocytopenia)</li>
          <li>Antidote: Protamine sulfate</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="info-block">
        <h3>🦵 5 P's — Neurovascular Assessment</h3>
        <table class="data-table">
          <thead><tr><th>P</th><th>Assessment</th><th>Normal Finding</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>Pain</strong></td><td>At rest and with passive motion</td><td>Controlled; not escalating</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Pulses</strong></td><td>Pedal and posterior tibial</td><td>Present and equal bilaterally</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Paresthesia</strong></td><td>Numbness, tingling, burning</td><td>None</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Paralysis</strong></td><td>Ability to move toes and foot</td><td>Movement present; equal bilaterally</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Pallor</strong></td><td>Skin color and temperature</td><td>Normal color and warmth bilaterally</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Clinical Reasoning: Boyd's right foot is cooler and his pedal pulse is slightly diminished compared to the left. What do you do?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>This is a priority finding requiring immediate notification of the provider.</strong></p>
        <ul>
          <li>Compare findings to baseline (pre-op and previous shift documentation)</li>
          <li>Is this new or established? A new finding is more urgent</li>
          <li>Assess for other signs of compromise: capillary refill &gt; 3 sec, cyanosis, increasing pain with passive motion</li>
          <li>Do NOT leave the patient alone — continue monitoring while calling for help</li>
          <li>Notify provider immediately with full SBAR</li>
          <li>Possible causes: edema compressing vessels, hematoma, thrombus, dressing too tight</li>
          <li>Document time, findings, actions taken, and provider notification</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <div class="phase-connector">⬇ You finalize your documentation and nursing diagnoses…</div>

  <!-- PHASE 6 -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="phase6">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Phase 6</span>
      <h2>Priority Diagnoses and Documentation</h2>
    </div>
    <h3>📋 Priority Nursing Diagnoses</h3>
    <div class="dx-rank-list">
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">1</span>
        <div><strong>Acute Pain</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: Pain 8/10; grimacing; guarding; tachycardia 96 bpm; splinting breathing</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">2</span>
        <div><strong>Ineffective Breathing Pattern</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: SpO₂ 93%; RR 20 shallow; crackles bilateral bases; fever 100°F; not using IS</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">3</span>
        <div><strong>Impaired Physical Mobility</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: Postoperative hip replacement; pain limiting movement; hip precautions required</div></div>
      </div>
      <div class="dx-rank-item">
        <span class="dx-number">4</span>
        <div><strong>Risk for DVT</strong><div class="dx-aeb">AEB: Immobility post-hip replacement; major orthopedic surgery — highest DVT risk category</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ SBAR — Calling Provider About Respiratory Status</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <div class="sbar-block">
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-s"><span class="sbar-label">S — Situation</span><p>Calling about Boyd Dubois, post-op day 1 following total right hip arthroplasty, with SpO₂ of 93% and inadequate respiratory effort secondary to pain.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-b"><span class="sbar-label">B — Background</span><p>Older adult male with history of osteoarthritis, hypothyroidism, and GERD. On morphine, acetaminophen, enoxaparin, levothyroxine, and pantoprazole. Last morphine was 4 hours ago. Patient has low-grade fever of 100°F at 24 hours post-op.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-a"><span class="sbar-label">A — Assessment</span><p>Pain 8/10; crackles at right base, diminished left base. SpO₂ 93%. Not using incentive spirometry due to pain. 5 W pattern is consistent with early atelectasis. I have administered ordered analgesic; plan to reassess in 30 minutes and coach IS when pain is controlled.</p></div>
          <div class="sbar-item sbar-r"><span class="sbar-label">R — Recommendation</span><p>Requesting: review of pain management plan — current analgesic interval may be insufficient; physical therapy consultation; confirm levothyroxine is being continued postoperatively.</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX A: Medications -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-a">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix A</span>
      <h2>Medication Review</h2>
    </div>
    <table class="data-table">
      <thead><tr><th>Medication</th><th>Class</th><th>Key Nursing Points</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Morphine</strong></td><td>Opioid analgesic</td><td>Monitor RR — hold if &lt; 12; assess sedation level; constipation risk; have naloxone available; HIGH ALERT medication</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Hydrocodone/Acetaminophen</strong></td><td>Opioid combination</td><td>Max acetaminophen 4 g/day total (from all sources); monitor for over-sedation</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Enoxaparin (Lovenox)</strong></td><td>LMWH anticoagulant</td><td>SQ abdomen; no aspiration; no rubbing; keep air bubble; monitor platelets (HIT); antidote: protamine sulfate</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Levothyroxine</strong></td><td>Thyroid hormone</td><td>Give on empty stomach 30–60 min before breakfast; do not give with calcium or iron; must be continued post-op to prevent myxedema</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Pantoprazole</strong></td><td>Proton pump inhibitor</td><td>GI protection; give before meals; reduces acid production; important with opioids and GI history</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX B: Q&A -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-b">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix B</span>
      <h2>Post-Simulation Questions &amp; Answers</h2>
    </div>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q1: What are the 5 W's of postoperative fever?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Wind (24–48 hrs):</strong> Atelectasis — most common cause of early postop fever</li>
          <li><strong>Water (48–72 hrs):</strong> UTI — often from catheter use</li>
          <li><strong>Wound (72 hrs+):</strong> Surgical site infection</li>
          <li><strong>Walking (5–7 days):</strong> DVT or PE</li>
          <li><strong>Wonder drugs (any time):</strong> Drug fever from medications</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q2: Why is levothyroxine critical to continue after surgery?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content"><p>Patients with hypothyroidism who miss levothyroxine doses post-operatively can develop <strong>myxedema coma</strong> — a rare but life-threatening complication of severely low thyroid hormone. Signs include profound hypothermia, bradycardia, hypotension, and altered mental status. Give levothyroxine on an empty stomach 30–60 min before breakfast; do not co-administer with calcium, iron, or antacids.</p></div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q3: What are early vs. late signs of DVT?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <p><strong>Early:</strong> Calf tenderness, swelling, warmth, redness; pitting edema in affected extremity</p>
        <p><strong>Late / PE signs:</strong> Sudden dyspnea, chest pain, tachycardia, decreased SpO₂, hemoptysis</p>
        <p>If PE suspected: activate rapid response; oxygen immediately; notify provider.</p>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q4: What are the 6 components of a complete pain assessment (OPQRST)?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li><strong>O — Onset:</strong> When did it start? Constant or intermittent?</li>
          <li><strong>P — Precipitating/Palliating:</strong> What makes it better or worse?</li>
          <li><strong>Q — Quality:</strong> What does it feel like? (Sharp, dull, throbbing, burning)</li>
          <li><strong>R — Region/Radiation:</strong> Where is it? Does it spread anywhere?</li>
          <li><strong>S — Severity:</strong> Scale 0–10; or FACES/behavioral scale as appropriate</li>
          <li><strong>T — Treatment/Impact:</strong> What has been tried? How does pain affect function and sleep?</li>
        </ol>
      </div>
    </details>
    <details class="reveal-block">
      <summary>▶ Q5: What are the three hip replacement precautions Boyd must follow to prevent dislocation?</summary>
      <div class="reveal-content">
        <ol>
          <li><strong>No hip flexion beyond 90°</strong> — do not bend the hip past a right angle</li>
          <li><strong>No adduction</strong> — do not cross legs or bring operative leg past midline</li>
          <li><strong>No internal rotation</strong> — do not turn toes inward</li>
        </ol>
        <p>Mnemonic: <strong>"No bending, no crossing, no turning in."</strong></p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>

  <!-- APPENDIX C: References -->
  <div class="phase-card" id="appendix-c">
    <div class="phase-header">
      <span class="phase-badge">Appendix C</span>
      <h2>References</h2>
    </div>
    <ol class="ref-list">
